{{Infobox writer | name = Alexander Kinloch Forbes | image =Alexander Kinloch Forbes.jpg | image_size = | caption = Portrait and signature of Alexander Kinloch Forbes | native_name = | native_name_lang = | pseudonym = | birth_name = | birth_date ={{Birth date|1821|7|7}} | birth_place = [[London]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1865|8|31|1821|7|7}} | death_place = Poona (now [[Pune]]) | occupation = Writer, judge | language = English, [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] | nationality = British | education = | alma_mater = [[East India Company College|Haileybury]] | period = | genres = | movement = | notableworks = Râs Mâlâ | spouse = Margaret Moir Forbes-Mitchell | partner = | children = Six | relatives = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | years_active = }} '''Alexander Kinloch Forbes''' ([[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]: એલેક્ઝાન્ડર કિન્લોક ફૉર્બસ) (1821–1865) was a scholar of the [[Gujarati language]] and a colonial administrator in [[British India]].
==Early life== Forbes was born in [[London]] on 7 July 1821 to John Forbes-Mitchell (1786-1822) of Thainston and Ann Powell (m. 1809 d. 1861). He was the youngest among six siblings.<ref name="Ranieval2013"/> He was christened on 9 August 1821 at St. Mary, St. Marylebone, London.<ref>"England Births and Christenings, 1538-1975," database, FamilySearch [https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:NYRF-CTY : 30 December 2014], Alexander Kinlock Forbes Mitchell, Alexander Kinlock Forbes Mitchell; citing, reference; FHL microfilm 580,910, 580,911, 580,912.</ref> He was educated at a school in [[Finchley]]. He articled to [[George Basevi]], an architect, for eight months but later joined a college [[East India Company College|Haileybury]] as he was appointed to Bombay Civil Service by [[Sir Charles Forbes, 1st Baronet|Sir Charles Forbes]] in 1840. He left it in 1842 and arrived in [[Bombay]], India in November 1843.<ref name="Shastriv2015">{{cite web | last=Shastri | first=Paul John & Parth | title=Forbes, Gujarati's renaissance man | website=The Times of India | date=31 August 2015 | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/Forbes-Gujaratis-renaissance-man/articleshow/48737160.cms | accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref><ref name="ForbesNairne1878">{{cite book|last1=Forbes|first1=|last2=Nairne|first2=|title=Râs Mâlâ: Hindoo Annals of the Province of Goozerat, in Western India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=opUBAAAAQAAJ&pg=PR15|year=1878|publisher=Richardson|pages=xv–xvi}}</ref>
==Administrative career== [[File:Alexander Kinloch Forbes Handwriting.png|thumb|Handwriting of Forbes]] He spent his initial two and half years as Assistant Collector of [[Ahmednagar]] and [[Khandesh]]. Later he was appointed as Assistant Judge in [[Ahmedabad]] in November 1846 where he noted the absence of literary society.<ref name="Shastriv2015"/> He served in different departments in Gujarat such as First Assistant Collector of Ahmedabad and Political Agent to [[Mahi Kantha Agency|Mahi Kantha]] until he went home in March 1854. During this period he collected material which was later published as ''Rasmala''. He went home in 1854 and returned at the end of 1856. He was appointed as Assistant Judge at [[Surat]] and later, in 1858, appointed on the same post at [[Khandesh]]. He want to return to Gujarat so he applied for vacant [[Kathiawar Agency|Political Agency of Kathiawar]]. It was turned down but later was moved to Kathiawar in September 1859 to subdue [[Indian rebellion of 1857|rebellion]] by [[Vagher]]s. The rebellion subdued by March 1860 and he returned to Surat as the Acting Judge. He was appointed as Secretary to Government in March 1861. He accepted post in [[Sadr Diwani Adalat|Sudder Court]] which, in August 1862, made him one of the first six Judges of [[Bombay High Court]] which he remained till his death. He also held the honorary post of Vice Chancellor of the [[University of Bombay]]. The A. Kinloch Forbes Gold Medal was awarded for proficiency in law at LL.B. Examination of the University.<ref name="ForbesNairne1878"/><ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20170721201601/http://bombayhighcourt.nic.in/libweb/puisnejudge/judges/ForbesAK.pdf</ref>
==Literature== He met [[Dalpatram]], a Gujarati poet, in 1848 who taught him Gujarati while Forbes encouraged him to write in Gujarati. They became close friends. He inspired Dalpatram to write ''Laxmi Natak'' published in 1849, the first play in Gujarati, based on Greek drama [[Plutus (play)|''Plutus'']].<ref name=toi>{{cite news|url=http://m.timesofindia.com/city/ahmedabad/Briton-inspired-Dalpatram-to-write-in-Gujarati-language/articleshow/30639604.cms|title =Briton inspired Dalpatram to write in Gujarati language|publisher=[[The Times of India]]|date=2014-02-22|accessdate=2014-02-22|last=Unnithan|first =Chitra}}</ref><ref name="Datta1988">{{cite book|author=Amaresh Datta|title=Encyclopaedia of Indian Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zB4n3MVozbUC&pg=PA1319|year=1988|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|isbn=978-81-260-1194-0|page=1319}}</ref>
On 26 December 1848 he started the [[Gujarat Vernacular Society]] in [[Ahmedabad]], which contributed to a literary renaissance in [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]. The fund of Rs 9601 was raised from locals, [[Baroda State]] and British officers. The society started the first public library, first school for girls, first periodical, first newspaper and first literary magazine of Gujarat.<ref name="Shastriv2015"/> He also founded Andrews Library in [[Surat]] in 1850 and Gujarati Sabha in [[Bombay]] in 1865. Gujarati Sabha was later renamed Farbas Gujarati Sabha after him. He organized conclave of Gujarati poets in 1852 at [[Idar State]]. Dalpatram's ''Farbesvilas'' was an account of these conclave.<ref name=toi/><ref name="Datta1988"/> He visited many Jain libraries in search of bards who told the stories of history of Gujarat. In 1856, he published ''Râs Mâlâ: Hindoo Annals of the Province of Goozerat, in Western India'' which documented the history from 8th century to arrival of British and folk literature of Gujarat in two volumes.<ref name=toi/><ref name="SinghGaur2008">{{cite book|author1=Surinder Singh|author2=I. D. Gaur|title=Popular Literature and Pre-modern Societies in South Asia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QVA0JAzQJkYC&pg=PA181|year=2008|publisher=Pearson Education India|isbn=978-81-317-1358-7|pages=181–182}}</ref> It was later translated into Gujarati by [[Ranchhodlal Udayaram Dave]] in 1869.<ref name="Datta1988"/> He also translated Dalpatram's essay ''Bhoot Nibandh'' as ''Demonology and Popular Superstitions of Gujarat''.
==Death== He died in Poona (now [[Pune]], [[Maharashtra]], India) in 31 August 1865 after brief illness.<ref name="Ranieval2013"/><ref name="ForbesNairne1878"/> Dalpatram composed ''Farbes viraha'', a Gujarati [[elegy]] in his memory.<ref name=toi/><ref name="Datta1988"/><ref name="HallWrigley2007">{{cite book|author1=Edith Hall|author2=Amanda Wrigley|title=Aristophanes in Performance, 421 BC-AD 2007: Peace, Birds and Frogs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fAjUXmBnNYUC&pg=PA117|year=2007|publisher=MHRA|isbn=978-1-904350-61-3|page=117}}</ref>
==Personal life== He married Margaret-Moir Forbes-Mitchell (1825-1 November 1904), daughter of Henry David Forbes-Mitchell of Bawlgownie, in Bombay on 25 March 1846.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Gentleman's Magazine, and Historical Chronicle, for the Year ...|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dewIAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA639|year=1846|publisher=Edw. Cave, 1736-&#91;1868&#93;|page=639}}</ref> They had six children; Edward Esme Forbes (1855-1920), Emmeline Maria Elizabeth Forbes, Margaret Theodora Lawrence Forbes (d. 1939), John Fraser Forbes (1847-1887), Henry David Erskine Forbes (1849-1920), Alexander Abernethie Forbes (b. 1851).<ref name="Ranieval2013">{{cite book|author=The Marquis of Ruvigny and Ranieval|title=The Plantagenet Roll of the Blood Royal: The Mortimer-Percy Volume|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uOHHuwI8tD4C&pg=PA228|date=May 2013|publisher=Heritage Books|isbn=978-0-7884-1872-3|pages=228–230}}</ref>
==Selected works== * {{cite book|author=Alexander Kinloch Forbes|title=Râs Mâlâ:Hindoo Annals of the Province of Goozerat, in Western India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s1woAAAAYAAJ|volume=1|year=1856|publisher=Richardson Bros.}}
