{{Infobox person | name = Mokbula Manzoor | native_name = ({{lang-bn|মকবুলা মনজুর}} | other_names = Makbula Manzoor | birth_date = 1938 | birth_place = [[Bangladesh]] | nationality = [[Bangladeshis|Bangladeshi]] | occupation = [[Author]] and [[novelist]] | years_active = 1968-2010 | known_for = Contributions to modern Bangladeshi literature }} '''Mokbula Manzoor''' or '''Makbula Manzoor''' ({{lang-bn|মকবুলা মনজুর}}, born 1938 (1939 or 1945 also cited)) is a [[Bangladesh]]i author and novelist. Author Syedur Rahman cites her together with [[Akhtaruzzaman Ilias]], [[Selina Hossain]] and [[Hasan Hafizur Rahman]] as one of the notable contributors to modern Bangladeshi literature.<ref name="Rahman2010">{{cite book|last=Rahman|first=Syedur|title=Historical Dictionary of Bangladesh|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bJfcCPUr0OoC&pg=PA185|date=27 April 2010|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-7453-4|page=185}}</ref>
Manzoor is noted for writing from a woman's perspective in a male-dominated society; her 1998 novel ''Kaler Mandira'' is one such example, and references female exploitation during the [[Bangladesh Liberation War]] in 1971. She is considered to be an outstanding Bangladeshi female writer, inspired by the events which led to the creation of the country in 1971.<ref name="Corporation2007">{{cite book|last=Corporation|first=Marshall Cavendish|title=World and Its Peoples: Eastern and Southern Asia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5ZBaVhmRvCkC&pg=PA477|date=September 2007|publisher=Marshall Cavendish|isbn=978-0-7614-7631-3|pages=477–}}</ref>
==Works==
===Novels=== * Ar Ek Jiban (Another Life, 1968) * Abasanna Gan (Tired Song,1982) * Baishakhe Shirna Nadi (The River Shrunk in Baishakh, 1983) * Jal Rang Chabi (Watercolour Painting, 1984) * Atmaja O Amra (Sons and Ourselves, 1988) * Patita Prithibi (The Fallen Earth, 1989) * Prem Ek Sonali Nadi (Love: A Golden River, 1989) * Shiyare Niyata Surja (The Perpetual Sun over the Lying Head, 1989); * Acena Nakshatra (The Unknown Star, 1990) * Kane Dekha Alo (Light for Observing the Bride, 1991) * Nirbacita Premer Upanyas (Selected Novels of Love, 1992); * Nadite Andhakar (Darkness on the River, 1996) * LilaKamal (Woman’s Toy Lotus, 1996) * Kaler Mandira (Time’s Cymbal, 1997)
==Awards== * Bangladesh Lekhika Sangha Prize (1984) * Qamar Kushtari Prize (1990) * Rajshahi Lekhika Sangha Literary Award (1993) * National Archives and Library Best Book Prize (1997) * [[Bangla Academy Literary Award]] (2006)
