{{redirect|Yora language|the Australian languages named Yor|Yuin–Kuric languages}} {{Infobox language |name=Yaminawa |nativename=Yaminahua |states=[[Peru]], [[Bolivia]], [[Brazil]] |region= |ethnicity = [[Yaminawá people|Yaminawá]] and related peoples |speakers=2,729 |date=2006–2011 |ref=e19 |speakers2=Est. 400 uncontacted speakers of Yora (2007) |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Panoan languages|Panoan]] |fam2=Mainline Panoan |fam3=Nawa |fam4=Headwaters |lc1=yaa|ld1=Yaminawa |lc2=ywn|ld2=Yawanawa |lc3=mcd|ld3=Sharanawa |lc4=swo|ld4=Shaninawa |lc5=mts|ld5=Yora |glotto=yami1255 |glottorefname=Yaminawa Complex }}
'''Yaminawa''' (Yaminahua) is a [[Panoan language]] of western Amazonia. It is spoken by the [[Yaminawá]] and some related peoples.
Yaminawa constitutes an extensive [[dialect cluster]]. Attested dialects are<ref name=Fleck>David Fleck, 2013, ''[http://digitallibrary.amnh.org/dspace/bitstream/handle/2246/6448/AP99.pdf?sequence=1 Panoan Languages and Linguistics]'', Anthropological Papers of the American Museum of Natural History #99</ref> ''two or more Brazilian Yaminawa dialects, Peruvian Yaminawa, Chaninawa, Chitonawa, Mastanawa, Parkenawa'' (= Yora or "Nawa"), ''Shanenawa'' (Xaninaua, = Katukina de Feijó), ''Sharanawa'' (= Marinawa), ''Shawannawa'' (= Arara), ''Yawanawa, Yaminawa-arara'' (obsolescent; very similar to Shawannawa/Arara), ''Nehanawa''<sup>†</sup>)
Very few Yaminawá speak Spanish or Portuguese, though the Shanenawa have mostly shifted to Portuguese.<ref>[http://www.ethnologue.com/%5C/15/show_language.asp?code=yaa "Yaminahua."] ''Ethnologue.'' (retrieved 25 June 2011)</ref>
== Phonology == The vowels of Yamanawa are /a, i, ɨ, u/. Yaminawa replaces /u/ with /ɯ/. Sharanawa, Yaminawa, and Yora have nasalized counterparts of the vowels, and these dialects demonstrate contrastive nasalization.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://linguistics.berkeley.edu/~saphon|title=SAPhon – South American Phonological Inventories|website=linguistics.berkeley.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-07-23}}</ref> {| class="wikitable" style="text-align:center" |+Consonants ! ![[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]] ![[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]] ![[Palato-alveolar consonant|Palato-alveolar]] ![[Retroflex consonant|Retroflex]] ![[Palatal consonant|Palatal]] ![[Velar consonant|Velar]] ![[Glottal consonant|Glottal]] |- ![[Stop consonant|Stop]] |p |t | | | |k | |- ![[Affricate consonant|Affricate]] | |t͡s |t͡ʃ | | | | |- ![[Fricative consonant|Fricative]] |β |s |ʃ |ʂ | | |h |- ![[Nasal consonant|Nasal]] |m |n | | | | | |- ![[Approximant consonant|Approximant]] | | | | |j |w | |- ![[Flap consonant|Flap]] | |ɾ | | | | | |} Yaminawa has a similar phonology to Yamanawa, but Yaminawa adds a [[voiced retroflex fricative]] /ʐ/ and replaces the [[voiced bilabial fricative]] /β/ with a [[voiceless bilabial fricative]] /ɸ/, and lacks the [[voiced labio-velar approximant]] /w/. Yora also lacks /ɸ/ and /w/. Sharanawa has /ɸ/ instead of /β/, and Shanewana has a labiodental fricative /f/ instead of /ɸ/.<ref name=":0" />
